These projectiles were originally loaded in the M48 .50 Spotter (or sometimes called .50 BAT) caliber cartridge and was used in conjunction with the M40 106mm Recoilless rifle.  The spotter charge in the projectile produces a flash and puff of white smoke to provide a significant visual indicator of the location upon impact.

These are quality reloads from Talon Manufacturing of West Virginia made in 2002. This is reliable sure-fire ammunition and has been stored in a controlled envronment.

title: For Sale:  Kel Tec KSG
postcontent:
The KSG (Kel-Tec Shotgun) is Kel-Tec CNCs first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape, and design is similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The KSG weighs 6.9 lbs. and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1 overall length and an 18.5 cylinder bore barrel. Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 12 rounds of 12 gauge 3 rounds in total (6 per tube). It can also reliably shoot shells as short as 1 3/4" up to the 3".
This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.

The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.


Caliber	12 gauge 3
Barrel length	18.5"
Total capacity	6+6+1
Weight empty	6.9lbs
Weight loaded	8.5lbs
Length	26.1"

title: For Sale:  CZ 40B - Excellent Condition - S&W 40
postcontent:
Considering selling my CZ40B in excellent condition


Comes with OEM Box and 1 - magazine


Learn more about the CZ40B from the CZForum online.  Here's a brief excerpt:


Per Milan trkulia (ref. http://www.czub.cz/en/shooting-team-czub.aspx?t=Photogallery&fotogalerie=foto-milan_trkulja#!prettyPhoto[pp_gal]/0/)


"Milan trkulia:  'You asking the right person as I was right on middle of it, when the Colt Z 40 happened.'


'Beside myself, another two persons you know very well, were instrumental in Colt Z or CZ .40 B project. It was Ira Kay and Kerby Smith....there was just one significant specification put forward by the Colt people - this pistol must bear exterior similarity with the the Colt 1911. It was just a verbal request, nothing was written down or signed on this design matter. We just shook the hands. That was it!


All another work was left on the CZ engineers. Shape of the pistol was designed by the Industrial Architect Vojtech Anderle (also author of CZ 100 design), and all interior mechanism works on Colt Z .40 was done by Radek Hauerland, who also worked with me later on CZ 2075 RAMI project. Your statement is absolutely correct, the Colt Z 40/CZ.40B pistol mechanism was fully adopted from CZ 75 line of pistols.


After CZ/Colt deal collapse, pistol was made by CZ for another customers, but in limited numbers. When Radek Hauerland worked on trigger mechanism for COLT Z .40, he at the same time got ready SA/DA and Decocker versions of this pistols. Therefore it was easy to later produce all these trigger mechanism versions, and also the caliber conversion down from .40 to 9x19 was very easy to make. Beside the Colt Z.40 and CZ .40 B pistols, there was an another model based on COLT Z .40 design produced in 9 x 19 cal and called the CZ LE 9.'


Its a great pistol designed from the beginning for the S&W .40.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 1876
postcontent: From my personal collection I have a beautiful Winchester Model 1876 Deluxe Sporting rifle chambered in the rarer 40-60 caliber. This Deluxe Model was manufactured in 1884 and shipped in 1886. It comes with a Factory letter of authenticity from the Cody Firearms Museum verifying all 4 special order features. Pistol Grip, Checkered Stocks, Case Hardened and a Set Trigger. With the 1876 Model see a total production of 63,871, there were only 9,275 rifles made with in a 40-60 caliber, 6,612 that came with a 28" octagon barrel and a mere 268 Deluxe Models with a pistol grip and checkered stocks. With some of those guns having round, 1/2 round and different barrel lengths, that makes this rifle quite rare. As for condition the receiver retains very little case color in protected areas and has faded to a mottled silver. It has a very nice appearance. The 28" octagon barrel and full magazine retain about 90% of their original bluing, starting to lighten in areas. The bluing looks much better in person, it appears lighter in photos. The highly figured XX grade, original walnut stocks are in very good condition, with normal handling marks and lightened checkering, more on the forearm. Most of the original high gloss piano finish remains. Some old timer lightly scratched (W.M. Little, ANIWA WIS) on the left side of the buttstock, it is barely seen (shown in photos #34 & #89). You don't really notice it in person. The wood to metal fit is tight and proud. I carefully removed the buttstock and the butt plate to show the matching assembly number 2633 stamped on them and the lower tang of the receiver. An "XX" is also stamped on the receiver tang. The action is tight and smooth, mechanically perfect. The Dustcover retains 90% of its original bluing and slides flawlessly. The bore is in excellent, mirror like condition with sharp rifling. I would rate it at 90% condition. Sights are original and perfect. The rear 38A Mid-Range Vernier peep sight is in excellent condition and is valued around $800 to $1000 alone. The barrel address and caliber markings are perfect. Screws are excellent and most appear unturned. Gun shows honest use, not abuse. This is a very rare Deluxe Model 1876 in better condition than most, with a lot of eye appeal. I have provided over 80 photos and offer a 3 day inspection period so you can bid with confidence. All photos were taken outdoors in natural light and provide a very accurate depiction of its condition. This old Winchester is considered an antique and can be shipped directly to you (No FFL Required). Insurance is provided with shipping.

title: For Sale:  Must Sell: Custom Remington 1911
postcontent:
I  am selling my custom Remington R1 1911 that's been extensively worked on and upgraded with Wilson Combat parts. The only reason I'm doing this right now is to pay for repairs on a vehicle that was in an accident mid last week, so I'm not going to be able to entertain any trade requests or drop the price as I'm already losing almost $350 to sell it quickly. First things first, here are the specs on the 1911 from the factory:

Caliber: .45 Auto
Magazine: 7+1
Barrel: Stainless
Twist: 1-16 LH
Overall Length: 8.5"
Overall Height: 5.5"
Trigger Pull: 3.5 - 5 lbs.
Finish: Satin Black Oxide
Grips: Double Diamond Walnut
Avg. Wt. (oz.): 38.5
MSRP: $729.00

With that said and done I'll tell you that a lot of time and energy has gone in to this weapon since I received it a month ago in trade, including a trigger job. The feed ramp has been polished, the barrel has been polished and throated. The base of the firing pin stop has been polished. The trigger bow has been polished and the trigger channel deburred. The sear and disconnector have been deburred and polished on the surfaces that required it. The sear spring has been polished and adjusted slightly.

With all the smithing out of the way on to the Wilson Combat parts that were fitted and installed: hammer, wide competition thumb safety, competition match trigger, beavertail. It comes with Pearce Grip rubber side panel grips. This firearm also has a match grade barrel installed in it. All in all what I have in to this weapon is nearly $950 when all things are said and done, not including what you'd normally spend on a gunsmith to do a trigger job and polish all the internals. which can easily be $75-150 depending on who you use. The only flaw is a small scratch next to the magazine release from the previous owner, but I had eventually planned to cerakote the frame in FDE and toss desert digital grips on it, so it didn't bother me. It has just about 200rds through it and it can run everything I put in to it. It's run Federal aluminum, TulAmmo steel, Winchester white box, and Remington gold saber without a single hiccup. This weapon is a super reliable tack driver now and would be great for home defense or EDC. I'm former law enforcement and do some firearm instruction and I would trust the lives of my family to it, it's that reliable.

I'm asking $600 out the door for this weapon and it will come with all the original stock parts, hard plastic Remington case, and two 7rd magazines. I will also require a valid FL driver's license and a bill of sale to be signed to protect both parties. If you have any questions or would like to see more pictures, please contact me. If you're going to offer less than I'm asking or to trade, please don't waste either of our time, this is a heck of a deal and it makes me sick to sell my project gun, but need outweighs toys.  Also, due to the vast price drop I will require the buyer to make the drive to Spring Hill, I'm already out quite a lot of money on this weapon.

Have a good one!
